\begin_layout Section
Fermi-Dirac
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For degenerate bands with carrier concentration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u & =N_{0}\,f\big(\pm\beta(\mu-E_{0})\big)\label{eq:fd-u}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 carrier concentration, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 quasi-Fermi level, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

 band energy level, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}=kT$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the Fermi-Dirac distribution function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f(x) & =\frac{1}{1+e^{x}}\label{eq:fd-f}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual, the convention is that the top sign corresponds to holes, and
 bottom to electrons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f^{-1}(z) & =\ln(z^{-1}-1)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Note the catastrophic cancellation if 
\begin_inset Formula $z\approx1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We derive the inverse relationship.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
u & =N_{0}\,f\big(\pm\beta(\mu-E_{0})\big)\\
\mu & =E_{0}\pm\frac{1}{\beta}f^{-1}(u/N_{0})
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
For holes, we conveniently have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
1-f(x) & =1-\frac{1}{1+e^{x}}\\
 & =\frac{1+e^{x}}{1+e^{x}}-\frac{1}{1+e^{x}}\\
 & =\frac{e^{x}}{1+e^{x}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{1+e^{-x}}\\
 & =f(-x)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{1-f(x)}{f(x)} & =1/f(x)-1\\
 & =e^{x}\label{eq:fp_over_f}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Degeneracy in Fermi-Dirac
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous part we assumed that the degeneracy of the band is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 We now relax that condition by turning the energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

 into an 
\emph on
effective
\emph default
 energy level, and relating it to the true energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the degeneracy when the band is empty (of whichever carrier type we
 chose to represent its carrier density), and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the degeneracy when the band is full.
 Following 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "(19.31)-(19.32)"
key "Marder2010a"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "Appendix B"
key "Shockley1952a"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, we have occupation probability
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p(E) & =\frac{1}{1+\frac{m_{0}}{m_{1}}e^{\pm\beta(\mu-E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}})}}\label{eq:fd-degen-occupation}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a sanity check, we see that we can recover the Maxwell-Boltzmann expression
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(E)\approx m_{0}e^{\mp\beta(\mu-E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}})}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p(E)\ll1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Comparing 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fd-u"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fd-f"

\end_inset

 against 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fd-degen-occupation"

\end_inset

, we can write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
e^{\pm\beta(\mu-E_{0})} & =\frac{m_{0}}{m_{1}}e^{\pm\beta(\mu-E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}})}\\
\mp\beta E_{0} & =\ln\frac{m_{0}}{m_{1}}\mp\beta E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}}\\
E_{0} & =E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}}\mp kT\ln\frac{m_{0}}{m_{1}}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which relates the effective energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}$
\end_inset

 to the true energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{0}^{\textnormal{true}}$
\end_inset

, where the upper sign is for holes and lower for electrons.
